folder: Flushing Avenue & Cypress Avenue, Brooklyn, NY
text:
(1) 1325 Flushing Ave., north side, east of Cypress Ave., showing in the foreground, the Nicholas Wyckoff farmhouse, acquired in 1765; from a Schenck. Another Nicholas Wyckoff was owner from 1852-1860. For more data see the N.Y. Sun. February 18, 1939. 1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, looking south, showing a rear view of the out-buildings of the farmhouse.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection. September 1928.

(3) The same, showing another angle. Note that one of the barns is partially demolished by fire.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection. September 1928.

(4) The same, showing another close up of the barn. It was erected in 1650 or 1656 (marked on rafter) and partially demolished by fire in 1700. The original joists remained and the barn was rebuilt around them. It was again partially destroyed by fire in March 1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection. 1922.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Cypress Avenue, Brooklyn, NY
text:
1325 Flushing Ave., north side, between Cypress Ave., and Seneca Avenue, showing in a set of four views the Nicholas Wyckoff home, also known as the Peter Wyckoff home. Views 1 and 2 are the same. No. 3 is a rear view, looking southwest towards Flushing Ave. No. 4 is a partial view of No. 2. Peter Wyckoff occupied this house during the Revolutionary War. Prior to this, in 1765, it was the Schenck farmhouse. In that year Nicholas Wyckoff acquired possession. Eugene L. Armbruster states that a broad hall runs through the center of the house, on the left side of the hall is a parlor and sitting room. On the other side of the hall is a dining room, kitchen, and three bedrooms. In the sitting room is a colonial mantle piece, having pictures of the old Rapelye, Johnson, and Wyckoff houses. The upper floors contain eight rooms and a garret. In a corner of the hall is an ancient grandfather clock still keeping time. See other views for more data. For more data see the N.Y. Sun, February 18, 1939.

September 1928.
Views 1 & 4.
Views 2 & 3: 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Cypress Avenue, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Flushing Ave., south side, from Cypress Ave (right background) to Peters Place (left not shown), showing in the background Peter Wyckoff's house. In toe foreground is Johnson Ave. At the right, partially seen on the Southwest corner of Cypress and Flushing Aves., is the Ehler's Coffee building. For more data see the N.Y. Sun, February 18, 1939.

April 1929.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
